title: Grateful Dead Live at Paramount Northwest Theater on 1972-07-21
lineage: Dat (Sony PCM-R500)(16/48) > Tascam DA-3000 (16/48)> Adobe Audition CC 2019 > TLH flac1648
description:
Set I
Promised Land, Sugaree, Black Throated Wind, Cumberland Blues, Bobby McGee, Loser, Mexicali Blues, China Cat Sunflower -> I Know You Rider, Beat It On Down The Line, Stella Blue, Playing In The Band, Tennessee Jed
Set II
Casey Jones, Weather Report Suite Prelude -> Me & My Uncle, Deal, Jack Straw, He's Gone, Truckin' -> Drums -> Jam -> The Other One -> Comes A Time, Sugar Magnolia -> Ramble On Rose, Goin' Down the Road Feeling Bad -> Not Fade Away

reviews.review_text:
You keep me up just one more night! "significant upgrade" just compare sound on Cumberland.

Set one
There are 3 weir tunes in a row early 
unless like me you consider Cumberland a Phil tune,
The set in front of us is mellow, 
Weir pulls out some of his ballads.
BTW, Me & Bobby (both out of the rotation bye & bye) 
and later Jerry lets Stella shine. 
 Stand alone STELLA's in the 1st set are INTENSE..
Loser, China>Rider, PITB make sure everybody feeling just right.
 Loser played since 71-- Jerry has it 100% down
Importance of Phil's vocals?--listen up during I Know You Rider
The P.I.T.B -Donna intro--(viva la difference!)
Jerry "put a little class in the act"
Most extended and psychedelic tune of the 1st set.
Donna's right on target bringing PITB home!
Mexicali, Biodtl, Jed -would be my 'least in preference' tunes 
but are all good to go here.
Mexicali- Phils backing vocals really make Mexicali
Biodtl- Donna Jean will soon stand this tune on Bobby's head.
Tenn Jed-reckon JED is a pretty rare set closer?
[There would be a bakers dozen this set 
if we had PROMISED opener -u can never tell.]
Set two 
Casey Jones, Me &My Uncle, Deal, Jack Straw
That is some pretty serious Outlaw Dead right there.
The Casey Jones starts out real rowdy then kinda coasts
WRS prelude>Me & My Uncle now that is unexpected.
Strong MAMU overall more memorable than the Casey Jones.
Deal- now here is a tune that Jerry could ignite with JGB.
This was my favorite Garcia 1st set closer by a mile.
well played here in the midst of up-tempo numbers.
As soon as they brought Garcia in on the vocals for Jack Straw
the tune become an instant GD standard
add Phil's backing vocals for that x-factor
He's Gone-this tune has grown up over the Europe 72 tour
Donna Jean is tucked in the backing vocals
on the front end of the tune
and more prominent on the 
"Nothings going to bring him back"
Once they build in the bridge
they will jam their way thru.>>>Under Construction.
Truckin>Drums>Other One>Comes a Time
Truckin especially the outro jam is tops throughout 1972
Drum kit not overly prominent in the mix
Sounds like Phil making the journey with Bill
There is a cut somewhere in there
but not sure Billy was ever an over the top drum solo guy.
11 minutes and a quarter before Bobby drops some TOO lyrics
They get pretty spacey right after those initial vocals
This Other One is a smoking crater of 22 minutes 
complete with a serious meltdown.
Haven't said anything about Keith
good to hear him tinkering and exploring..
Strange to think about how Drums>Space 
got so institutionalized
Eyewitness to Jerry doing Comes a Time in 85
serious showstopper!
(The Stella from this show is all that as well.)
Sugar Magnolia and the kitchen sink..

This is a G-R-A-T-E shows 
with the band at the apex of their sound.
